arXiv.abstract:
This paper analyzes a new self-avoiding (SA) meshwork model using the canonical Monte Carlo simulation technique on lattices that consist of connection-fixed triangles. The Hamiltonian of this model includes a self-avoiding potential and a pressure term. The model identifies a crumpled-to-tubule (CT) transition between the crumpled and tubular phases. This is a second-order transition, which occurs when the pressure difference between the inner and outer sides of the surface is close to zero. We obtain the Flory swelling exponents $
u_{{m R}^2}(=\!D_f/2)$ and $ ar{
u}_{m v}$ corresponding to the mean square radius of gyration $R_g^2$ and enclosed volume $V$, where $D_f$ is the fractal dimension. The analysis shows that $ ar{
u}_{m v}$ at the transition is almost identical to the one of the smooth phase of previously reported SA model which has no crumpled phase.

The branching fractions of radiative leptonic $	au$ decays $(	au 	o l 
u  ar{
u} \gamma$, $l=e,\mu)$ were recently measured by the Babar collaboration with a relative error of about 3%. The measurement of the branching ratio $\mathcal{B} (	au 	o e  ar{
u} 
u \gamma)$, for a minimum photon energy of 10 MeV in the $	au$ rest frame, differs from our recent SM prediction by 3.5 standard deviations, whereas our result agrees with Babar's value for $\mathcal{B} (	au 	o \mu  ar{
u} 
u \gamma)$. Our predictions also agree with the measurement of $\mathcal{B} (\mu 	o e  ar{
u} 
u \gamma)$ by the MEG collaboration. We also report on a recent proposal to test the $	au$ dipole moments via precise measurements of radiative leptonic $	au$ decays at high-luminosity $B$ factories.
